grep - grep [flags] pattern [file...]
Flags.
-i  ignores Case-insensitive match - grep -i "error" * #* search current folder for -> (ERROR, error, Error)
-w  Match whole words only (not substrings)- grep -w "root" /etc/passwd → Only the exact word "root", not "rootkit" or "subroot"
-r / -R Recursively search directories #grep -r "Error" my_project/
 flag -r (or --recursive) #ignore links(like a desktop shortcut to another places) to other directories and do files of files.
 flag -R (or --dereference-recursive) searches everything files, directories and links to other places. 
-A n /-B n Print n lines after or before each match (these can be combined)
  #grep -B 5 -A 3 "error" file.log -> Shows 5 lines before + 3 lines after each match.
-H — Always print filename - grep -H "error" app.log # Output: app.log:error message here
 useful when Searching multiple files with grep -r (recursive), or forcing filename display.
-v — Invert match (exclude) Shows lines that do NOT contain the pattern. 
 grep -v "DEBUG" app.log # Show all lines except DEBUG ## grep -v "^#" config.conf # Show lines that are not comments
-o — Only show the matched part ## grep -o "http://[^ ]*" file.txt # Output: only the URLs, not the whole line
 used for extracting specific patterns (IP addresses, emails, URLs, etc.)
-E — Extended Regular Expressions, Extended regex (same as egrep). Enables +, ?, |
grep -E "error|warning|failed" file.log
grep -E "[0-9]{3}" file.log          # Match 3-digit number
-c — Count matches #Counts how many lines match the pattern.
 grep -c "ERROR" server.log   # e.g. output: 42
 grep -c "error" *.log  # Count per file (all .log file)
-n — Show line numbers Displays the line number before each matching line.
 grep -n "function" script.sh # Output:  15:function main() {
--color — Colorize output #Highlights the matching text in color (usually red).
 grep --color "error" app.log
