find Traverse directory trees to locate files/directories matching criteria.
- Works on metadata (name, size, time, permissions) — not file contents.
find [path] [expression]
FLAGS
-Finding by Identity (-name / -iname): -name (Case-Sensitive):find . -name "report.txt" #just returns report.txt
 flag -iname (Case-Insensitive): The "i" stands for ignore case. find . -iname "*.jpg" #all matching jpg files regardless of case
-Finding by Structure (-type):type - f Regular file, -type d Directory Folders / directories -type l Symbolic link
 find . -type f -name "*.txt" # Find all .txt files
 find /var -type d -name "logs"  # Find all directories named "logs" usually easier with other flags
 find /usr -type l # Find all symlinks
-Finding by Size 
 The Math Modifiers (+, -, or nothing) - The sign you place directly in front of the number tells find
 whether you are looking for an exact match or a range.
 +n (Greater than): Finds files larger than the size you specified.
 -n (Less than): Finds files smaller than the size you specified.
 n (Exact match): Finds files that are exactly that size (rounded up to the nearest unit)

 The Unit Scales - You must attach a single character to the end of your number to let the computer know
 what scale of measurement you are using. 
 Character    UnitScale   What it stands for
 b            Blocks         512-byte blocks (This is the default if you omit the unit!).
 c            Bytes          Exact bytes (Think "characters"). #find . -type f -size 0c
 w            Words          2-byte words.
 k            Kilobytes      $1024$ bytes. #find . -type f -size -10k 
 M            Megabytes      $1,048,576$ bytes (Must be uppercase!). 
 G            Gigabytes      Over $1$ billion bytes (Must be uppercase!). #find /var -type f -size +2G - bigger than 2 gigabyte 

 The "Rounding Up" Trap ⚠️
 One technical detail is how 'find' handles rounding when using large units like M or G without a + or - modifier.
 If you search for find . -size 1M, Bash doesn't look for a file that is exactly $1,048,576$ bytes down to the last digit.
 It rounds everything up to the nearest Megabyte block. So, a file that is 500 Kilobytes gets rounded up to 1M 
 and will show up in your results! If you ever need an exact, absolute byte match, always use the lowercase c unit:
   find . -type f -size 1000c  # Finds a file that is exactly 1,000 bytes, not a single byte more or less

-Finding by Timeline (-mtime / -newer)
 flag -mtime (Modification Time):Finds files modified a specific number of days ago. +7 means more than 7 days ago; 
 -7 means less than 7 days ago. 
   find /var/log -type f -mtime -2  # Find logs modified within the last 48 hours (less than 2 days)
 flag -newer [file]: Finds files that have been modified more recently than a specific reference file.
  find /etc -type f -newer /backup/last_safe_backup.cfg   # Find any configuration file changed since you last made a backup file
-Finding by Ownership (-user / -group) - Filters files based on who owns them or which team group they belong to.
  find /home -user fawaz -group selfexplanatory
-Finding by Security (-perm) - Filters files based on their numeric permissions. 
  find . -type f -perm 644 #644 means the owner can read/write, but everyone else can only read.
-Controlling Depth (-maxdepth n) - By default, find will dive down thousands of subfolders deep. 
  flag -maxdepth sets a hard limit on how many folders deep it is allowed to travel. 
  -maxdepth 1 means "only search the directory I point to; do not open any subfolders inside it."
  find /etc -maxdepth 1 -name "*.conf"  # Search only the immediate /etc directory, skipping subfolders
  e.g  -maxdepth 3 -> Depth 3: Files inside two levels of subfolders (e.g. /etc/nginx/conf.d/default.conf)
-Taking Action (-exec vs -delete) : These flags tell find what to do with the results instantly. 
The Action Executor: -exec cmd {} \;
 This runs a completely separate Linux command (cmd) against every single file found.
  {}: This is a placeholder. find automatically replaces {} with the name of the file it just discovered.
  \;: This marks the absolute end of the command you are running inside -exec. 
  The backslash is required to escape the semicolon so Bash doesn't get confused.
   find /data -type f -name "*.png" -exec cp {} /backup/images/ \;  # Copy all found .png images into a central backup folder
   How -exec works:
    -exec : Tells find to run a command on each matched file.
    {} : Placeholder — replaced by the full path of each found file.
    cp : Copy command.
   /backup/images/ : Destination directory (must exist beforehand).
   \; : Ends the -exec command (required syntax).
The Nuclear Option: -delete
An optimized, built-in action that instantly deletes every file that matches your search criteria.
⚠️ Warning: Never run a -delete command without running the search normally first to see what it hits!
find . -type f -name "*.tmp" -delete # Instantly wipe out all temporary files in your project directory
