CUT : Extract specific columns or character ranges from each line of text. Think of it as a lightweight column selector for structured text like CSV or TSV files.
The cut command in Linux is a fast, lightweight utility designed to slice up lines of text and extract specific pieces of data. 
Think of it like a digital box cutter that can slice your text either vertically by columns (using a delimiter like a comma or colon) or horizontally by exact character positions.
cut [flags] [file...]
FLAGS
Slicing by Columns (-d and -f) #d only works with f
These flags are almost always used together. They allow you to cut text based on a
specific character that separates your data fields (like a CSV file or system config).

-d ':' (Delimiter)
The -d flag specifies the delimiter—the boundary character that splits the text into columns.
By default, cut assumes tabs, so if your file uses colons, commas, or spaces, you must declare it here.
Example: -d ':' tells cut to treat every colon as a wall separating columns.

-f 1,3 (Specific Fields)
The -f flag stands for fields (columns). You specify exactly which column numbers you want to keep,
separated by commas.
Example: Extracts only the 1st and 3rd columns, throwing everything else away.

-f 2-5 (Field Range)
Instead of loose commas, you can use a dash to extract a continuous range of columns.
Example: Extracts columns 2, 3, 4, and 5.
 cut -d ':' -f 1,3 /etc/passwd #takes: username:password:UID:GID:GECOS:home_directory:shell -returns root:0 etc.
daemon:1

Slicing by Exact Positioning (-c and -b) -If your data doesn't have dividers like commas or colons,
but every line has an exact layout (fixed-width text), you cut by character or byte positions instead.

-c 1-10 (Character Range)
The -c flag slices text based on character positions, regardless of what those characters are.
Example: This will clip out exactly the first 10 characters on every line.

-b (Bytes)
The -b flag slices by exact byte positions. The Difference: In plain English text, 
1 character equals 1 byte, so -c and -b behave identically. However, if your text contains 
complex international characters or emojis (which take up 2 to 4 bytes per character), 
-b cuts raw data bytes, which might split an emoji in half and cause weird text corruption.
Stick to -c unless you are auditing raw binary data.

cut -c 1-15 /var/log/auth.log # Grabs just the date/time stamp from the start of the log entries

Advanced Behavior Modifiers (--complement and -s)
--complement (The Inverter)
This flag completely flips your selection. Instead of keeping the fields or characters you specified, 
cut hides them and outputs everything else.
 cut -d ':' -f 1-6 --complement etc/passwd/ -> /root:/bin/bash instead of - root:x:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash

-s (Only Only Lines Containing Delimiters)
The -s flag stands for silent or only-delimited. By default, if cut processes a line that does not contain
the delimiter you specified with -d, it prints the whole line unmodified. -s forces cut to completely skip 
and ignore lines that don't match your delimiter format.
 cut -d ':' -f 1 -s database.txt #prints fawaz from :# User Database Update /n fawaz:x:1000:1000 -ignores user database because there is no delimiter :
